# <%= current_page.data.title %>

Use this path when automation is not available or cannot be used safely during an incident.

## When to use this path

- Azure DevOps pipelines are unavailable.
- Azure DevOps private agent pool is unavailable (AKS offline)
- Service connection or agent pool issues block automation.
- You need manual control over each stage.

## Restore Guide

### Step 1: Create a new storage container for restoration

1. You will need Storage account access to complete this step, one of:
    - Owner, Contributor, Storage Account Contributor, Storage Account Blob Contributor
    - See [Requesting RBAC access via Access Packages](../../Access-and-Permissions/rbac-access-packages.html) for how to request elevated access if you don't have the required role already.
    - Note that some PIM activation and Access Package requests might require approval making this process impossible with a single person. In a DR scenario this is unlikely to be a blocker as it will be triggered by the business with multiple technical staff involved, but be aware of the risk in out-of-hours situations.
2. Access the vault storage account for the platform:
    - CNP: `cnpvaultrestorationprod`
    - CPP: `sacppvaultrestoreprd`
3. Navigate to `data storage` and `containers`
4. Finally select `Add Container` to create a new container for the restore
    - Use this naming convention for manual restores: `<instance-name>-<mmhh>-<ddmmyy>-manual-restore` e.g. `plumv14flexiblesandbox-5613-200326-manual-restore`

### Step 2: Trigger vault restore to storage

1. Open [Azure Portal](https://portal.azure.com/).
2. Navigate to the Backup Vault `cnp-backup-vault`.
3. Select `Backup Instances` on the left menu and check that the filters are set to `datasource type == Azure Database for PostgreSQL Flexible server`
4. From the filtered list find the PostgreSQL instance name you want to restore
5. On the new page, a list of restore points will appear (if any are available) and you can view details by selecting `view`.
6. Select the `...` and click restore on the restore point you want to use.
7. This will trigger the restore options and you can now enter the necessary information
    - Restore Point - should be selected for you if you used the `...` option but if not you can select the relevant restore point here.
    - Restore parameters
      - Target storage account: CNP: `cnpvaultrestorationprod`, CPP: `SACPPVAULTRESTOREPRD`
      - Target Container: Name of container created in step 1.
8. Once selected you can complete this step and return to the restore menu
9. A validate option will now appear, it is important to select `validate` to ensure access is possible for the Backup Vault managed Id.
10. If validation is successful, continue to the review+restore page, review the settings and trigger restore when ready.

When complete all dump files from the backup will be restored to the Storage Account Container and are now available to restore to a PostgreSQL instance.

### Step 3: Prepare target PostgreSQL server in UK South

1. To restore the dump files first there needs to be a target server
2. If building manually you can use the Azure [documentation](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/postgresql/configure-maintain/quickstart-create-server#create-server-using-azure-portal) to complete this step.
    - You will need to have access to the subscription and resource group that you want to build in
3. When you have a target server, ensure any private networking, subnet and DNS are correct.
    - If a private endpoint is being used, make sure the F5 VPN is available first otherwise you cannot access the PostgreSQL server
    - The virtual network used for the new PostgreSQL instance must be peered to the hub to allow F5 VPN access
4. Ensure required extensions/server parameters are aligned for workload needs.
    - The source server may have specific extensions enabled, these may be required to restore full functionality beyond the data restoration.
5. When built, confirm access via the credentials used for the build (via F5 VPN if necessary)

### Step 4: Restore blobs to database

The following [documentation](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/backup/restore-azure-database-postgresql-flex#restore-the-backup-files-from-storage-container-to-a-new-or-existing-postgresql--flexible-server) exists from Microsoft. This provides a complete guide alongside the below.

<%= warning_text('Do not restore <code>_schema.sql</code> on Flexible Server — the <code>*_database_*.sql</code> dump files already include schema. Running <code>_schema.sql</code> separately will cause duplicate object errors. To verify a dump file includes schema, run: <code>pg_restore --list &lt;db-file&gt;.sql | head -50</code> and look for TABLE, SEQUENCE, INDEX or FUNCTION entries.') %>

<%= warning_text('<code>_tablespace.sql</code> is not applicable to Flexible Server and should not be restored.') %>

1. You will need the following access:
    - Storage Account Blob Contributor, Storage Account Blob Reader
2. Access the storage account container and download all `*_database_*.sql` files from the container.
3. Download `*_roles.sql` if role replay is required (recommended when possible).

   <%= warning_text('Role replay on managed PostgreSQL requires filtering of superuser-only attributes before use, otherwise the restore will fail with permission errors.') %>

    - Clean the roles file before use:

    ```bash
    sed -i '/azure_superuser/d; /azure_pg_admin/d; /azuresu/d; /^CREATE ROLE replication/d; /^ALTER ROLE replication/d; /^ALTER ROLE/ {s/NOSUPERUSER//; s/NOBYPASSRLS//;}' roles.sql
    ```

4. When ready, restore the roles.sql file before any database files:

    ```bash
    psql "host=<host> port=<port> user=<username> dbname=postgres sslmode=require" -v ON_ERROR_STOP=0 -f roles.sql
    ```

5. With roles restore create empty target database(s).
    - Each dump file `*_database_*.sql` is named for a database e.g. this file would contain the `rhubarb` data `c4c64b98-971e-44fc-8df8-8f4427b417a2_database_rhubarb.sql`
    - You will need to create a database for each dump file
      - The following can be ignored as they are defaults from Azure
        - azure_maintenance
        - azure_sys
        - postgres
        - templateX (there may be more than one starting at 0 - `template0`)
6. With each database ready you can restore the data with `pg_restore` using admin account and `--no-owner`.

Example command:

```bash
pg_restore -h <postgres-server-url> -p <port> -U <username> -d <database-name> --no-owner -v <db-file-name>
```

## Validation and handover

1. Validate data exists in the databases by listing the databases

   ```bash
   psql "host=<host> port=5432 user=hmctsAdmin dbname=postgres sslmode=require" -c "\l"
   ```

2. Validate row counts or key data checks for priority tables:

   ```bash
   psql "host=<host> port=5432 user=hmctsAdmin dbname=<dbname> sslmode=require" \
     -c "SELECT schemaname, tablename, n_live_tup FROM pg_stat_user_tables ORDER BY n_live_tup DESC LIMIT 20;"
   ```

3. Validate application connectivity and critical read/write checks.
4. Record restore point, timings and any deviations.
5. Hand over to service/application teams for functional validation.

